            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "The son of a pragmatic Japanese-American engineer and a free-spirited artist from Sonoma wine country, Kenji Miller\u2019s life has been a blend of disciplined structure and sensory passion. Growing up in San Jose, he was taught the value of precision and hard work by his father, but his true education happened during summer visits to his mother\u2019s family vineyard. There, surrounded by the earthy scent of grapes and oak, he discovered a world that spoke to his soul, a language of terroir and tannins.\n\nInitially bowing to his father\u2019s practicality, Kenji pursued an undergraduate degree in business. He found the work stable but sterile. The turning point came during a trip to France at age 25, where a meal in Lyon, paired with a Burgundy so profound it felt like a revelation, changed his trajectory. He promptly enrolled in a graduate program for Hospitality Management at Cornell. It was there he met a mentor, an old-world sommelier who saw Kenji\u2019s rare combination of a scientific mind and a poet\u2019s palate. This set him on the grueling path to becoming a Master Sommelier.\n\nThe pursuit was all-consuming, requiring multiple attempts and personal sacrifices, including his marriage, which ended amicably under the strain of his relentless study and travel. Achieving the title was his life\u2019s greatest triumph, a validation of his passion over pragmatism.\n\nNow 47, Kenji is the lead sommelier at a Michelin-starred restaurant in SoMa. His daily 5.5-mile MUNI ride from his modest Cole Valley apartment is a meditative ritual, a quiet buffer before the performance of evening service. He lives a life of curated simplicity; his small apartment is filled with books and a meticulously organized wine collection, but few other possessions. He maintains a close circle of industry friends who understand his demanding lifestyle. Kenji\u2019s connection to San Francisco is rooted in its culinary landscape\u2014a city that appreciates the artistry he dedicates his life to. His dream is to one day open a small, unassuming wine bar in his neighborhood, a place focused on education and discovery, where he can share the bottle that changes someone else's life."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, standing with his mother between rows of Zinfandel vines, the Sonoma sun warming his neck. She handed him a single, dusty grape. \"Crush it with your tongue,\" she whispered, \"don't just chew.\" He did, and the world bloomed\u2014sun, earth, and a hint of pepper. It wasn't just fruit; it was a story. In that moment, he understood his mother\u2019s language, a dialect of the senses that his father\u2019s precise world of engineering could never fully capture. It rooted him in a world of taste.\n\n2.\nIt was a simple bistro in Lyon, the air thick with garlic and chatter. Then the wine, a Morey-Saint-Denis, arrived. The first sip silenced everything. It wasn't just a drink; it was history, geology, and poetry. The structure he learned from his father, the soul from his mother\u2014it was all there in the glass. At 25, his pre-written life dissolved. He saw a new path, narrow and difficult, but true. He looked up from the glass, his future finally in focus. In that moment, he chose the wine.\n\n3.\nHe was 36. After the three-day Master Sommelier exam, he stood staring at the list of names posted on the door. His was not on it. The air left his lungs, a hollow ache of failure spreading through his chest. He saw his father\u2019s pragmatic disappointment in his mind\u2019s eye. But then, a quiet coldness set in. Not anger, but resolve. This blinding pursuit was his to finish, no matter the cost. The failure didn't break him; it forged him into the disciplined professional he needed to become.\n\n4.\nThey opened a 2005 Schramsberg, the same vintage they\u2019d served at their wedding. The fog muted the city outside. There were no tears, just a quiet, profound sadness. \u201cYour path is a singular one, Kenji,\u201d his wife said, her smile gentle. He knew she was right. They clinked glasses, not to a shared future, but in memory of their past. At 41, he learned that pursuing a perfect obsession sometimes requires the sacrifice of a perfect partnership. The solitude it left behind became his companion.\n\n5.\nJust last year, a young couple at table seven seemed intimidated by the wine list. He approached, not as an authority, but a guide. He poured them a glass of Savenni\u00e8res, explaining its flinty, honeyed secrets. He watched from across the room as the woman took a sip, her eyes widening. She looked at her partner, speechless, and he saw his own Lyon epiphany reflected in her face. In that moment, he wasn't just serving wine; he was opening a door. This quiet act of sharing, he realized, was his life's purest triumph."
